README.md
PLP 3: Conditional Statements and Logical Operators in PHP
Overview
This repository contains both a textual explanation and executable PHP code demonstrating the use of conditional statements and logical operators in PHP. These examples illustrate how PHP handles decision-making through if/else, if/elseif/else, switch-case, short-circuit evaluation, and the dangling else problem.
________________________________________
Contents
1. Explanation Document
•	The file PLP3_Conditional_Logic_PHP.txt contains a detailed narrative explaining: 
o	Boolean values in PHP
o	Types of conditional statements (if/else, if/elseif/else, switch-case)
o	Short-circuit evaluation
o	Handling of the dangling else problem
o	Behavior of switch-case, including break and continue
2. PHP Code File
•	The file plp3_conditionals.php includes PHP examples with well-commented code that: 
o	Demonstrates different conditional statements
o	Provides an example of short-circuit logic
o	Shows how PHP resolves the dangling else issue
o	Explores switch-case behavior

How to Run the PHP Code
Prerequisites
•	Ensure you have PHP installed on your system. You can check by running: 
•	php -v
•	If PHP is not installed, download it from the official PHP website.
Executing the PHP Script
1.	Navigate to the project directory where plp3_conditionals.php is saved.
2.	Run the script using the command: 
3.	php plp3_conditionals.php
4.	The expected output should match the comments provided in the script.

Expected Output
When executed, the PHP script should output the following:
x is true
You got a B!
Start of the workweek.
Logging in...
User is logged in.
Else belongs to which if?
Else correctly paired!
Good job!
One
Two

